    // Case B: $1^a 0^b$ (where $a+b=n$).
    // Requires $a \le 1$ OR $b \le 1$.
    // B1: $a=n, b=0 \implies 1^n$. (Covered by Cost1)
    // B2: $a=0, b=n \implies 0^n$. (Covered by Cost0)
    // B3: $a=1, b=n-1 \implies 10^{n-1}$. Cost to achieve: $\text{Count of '0's in } s \text{ at position 0} + \text{Count of '1's in } s \text{ at positions } [1, n-1]$.
